The paper discusses a novel physics-based approach to computation called Memcomputing, which leverages the property of memory (time non-locality) to efficiently solve hard problems. The approach involves using digital memcomputing machines (DMMs) that are scalable and can be realized with non-linear dynamical systems with memory. The paper discusses the self-organizing logic gates used in DMMs, which are "terminal-agnostic" and do not distinguish between input and output terminals. The paper also discusses the collective dynamical behavior of DMMs, which is reminiscent of a phase transition or the "edge of chaos." Based on these topics, the most likely arXiv CS sub-categories for this paper are cs.ET (Emerging Technologies), cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing), cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms), cs.CC (Computational Complexity), and cs.LG (Machine Learning).
